WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.200
Who has ever tried to get 100% test coverage in one of their code bases?

00:05.200 --> 00:09.040
Raise your hand so I can shame you.

00:09.040 --> 00:10.800
I think it's a fool's errand, right?

00:10.800 --> 00:13.920
I think it's a fool's errand to go after 100% test coverage,

00:13.920 --> 00:17.040
and there are people that vehemently disagree with me.

00:17.040 --> 00:19.120
But I think it makes you end up testing things

00:19.120 --> 00:23.120
that are just not important to be tested.

00:23.120 --> 00:27.840
That being said, I'm going to show you just the greatest and easiest hack

00:27.920 --> 00:32.800
to do 100% test coverage, and it's called Snapshot Testing.

00:32.800 --> 00:38.320
And I show it to you because it's a low effort, low confidence way of testing.

00:39.680 --> 00:41.840
And as soon as you say low confidence, I'm out.

00:42.400 --> 00:44.240
If it's low confidence, then what am I doing?

00:44.240 --> 00:45.120
Why am I doing this?

00:47.200 --> 00:51.440
But they're so easy to write that I'll kind of let you be the judge of it.

00:52.080 --> 00:53.040
Some people do like them.

00:53.040 --> 00:54.320
I think they're kind of discouraged now,

00:54.320 --> 00:56.560
but they're so fast to show that I was like, yeah, might as well.

00:57.440 --> 00:58.880
So we're going to make another file here.

00:58.880 --> 01:00.080
We're going to test which file here.

01:00.080 --> 01:04.000
We're going to test cart.jsx, so cart.test.jsx.

01:04.800 --> 01:08.400
This is just a dumb display component, right?

01:08.400 --> 01:10.400
It doesn't really do very much other than display stuff.

01:10.400 --> 01:14.320
So this is actually the best case scenario for using Snapshot Testing.

01:14.880 --> 01:18.560
The only thing Snapshot Testing does is it renders out the entire component

01:18.560 --> 01:22.320
and says it looks like this, and then it tracks that.

01:22.320 --> 01:24.480
And so if you run that Snapshot Test again,

01:24.480 --> 01:26.720
and it looks different than it did last time you ran it,

01:27.360 --> 01:28.880
then it fails the test.

01:28.880 --> 01:30.320
It says something changed.

01:31.120 --> 01:34.560
You can either update this or something happened that you didn't anticipate.

01:36.560 --> 01:37.280
I'll show you what I mean.

01:38.880 --> 01:44.160
Import, expect, and test from the test.

01:45.280 --> 01:52.480
Import, render from at testing library.

01:53.280 --> 01:59.120
And import cart from dash dash cart.

02:02.720 --> 02:07.440
Test snapshot with nothing in cart.

02:12.800 --> 02:14.480
You can make this async if you want to.

02:14.480 --> 02:15.920
I didn't in my notes, so I won't here.

02:18.080 --> 02:20.800
So you can say const as fragment.

02:22.960 --> 02:23.920
Equals render.

02:28.640 --> 02:29.360
There we go.

02:29.360 --> 02:32.000
Cart, cart.

02:39.760 --> 02:45.120
Okay, and then you're going to say expect as fragment,

02:45.840 --> 02:52.080
which is a function to match Snapshot.

02:52.880 --> 02:56.480
That's it.

02:56.480 --> 02:58.960
That is the entire test that you have to write right there.

